    <title>Combined summary - [BIP draft] Consensus-enforced transaction replacement signalled via sequence numbers</title>
    <updated>2023-06-09T22:11:05.092317+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-June/008450.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Mark Friedenbach has proposed a soft-fork change to the consensus-enforced behavior of sequence numbers in Bitcoin to enable safe transaction replacement via per-input relative lock-times. The proposal repurposes the nSequence field of a transaction input as a consensus-enforced relative lock-time, using the full range of the 32-bit sequence number and making it semantically compatible with the originally envisioned use of sequence numbers for fast mempool transaction replacement.However, there are external constraints that limit the full range of sequence numbers when interpreted as a relative lock-time, and repurposing nSequence may prevent its use in other contexts. To address this, the relative lock-time semantics are enforced only if the most significant bit of nSequence is set. This preserves 31 bits for alternative use when relative lock-times are not required.Stephen Morse has given constructive criticism that an OP_RCLTV may still be necessary in cases involving multiple signing parties. The email conversation thread also discusses potential issues with an inverted version of CSV and CLTV, and the need for OP_RCLTV in certain situations.The BIP draft and reference implementation can be found on GitHub. Despite some criticism, Friedenbach hopes to propose an additional BIP covering the CHECKSEQUENCEVERIFY opcode and its enabling applications.The proposal has several advantages, such as making use of the full range of the 32-bit sequence number and being semantically compatible with the originally envisioned use of sequence numbers for fast mempool transaction replacement. However, there are external constraints that prevent the full range of sequence numbers from being used when interpreted as a relative lock-time, and re-purposing nSequence as a relative lock-time precludes its use in other contexts.The email conversation is regarding the proposal of a soft-fork change to the consensus-enforced behavior of sequence numbers for supporting safe transaction replacement via per-input relative lock-times. The proposed architecture aims to enable safe transaction replacement by repurposing the nSequence field of a transaction input to be a consensus-enforced relative lock-time.The discussion also considers the possibility of implementing "not after" in Bitcoin script, which would make a script that was once valid later invalid. However, this wouldn't be compatible with the current model of reprocessing transactions in later blocks if the block they were first in gets reorged. Overall, Mark Friedenbach's proposal has the potential to make transaction replacement safer and more efficient. However, there are concerns about external constraints that limit the full range of sequence numbers when interpreted as a relative lock-time and the need for additional opcodes in certain use cases.</summary>
